Spring is made up of several modules. Here are the most important ones for backend development:

a. Core Container:
What it does: Provides the fundamental features, including IoC and DI.
Key classes: ApplicationContext, BeanFactory.
Usage: All Spring applications use this module.

b. Aspect-Oriented Programming (AOP):
What it does: Allows you to separate cross-cutting concerns (like logging, security,
transactions) from business logic.
Example: You can add logging to all methods in a package without changing their code.
Implementation: Use @Aspect and @Around, @Before, @After annotations.
Ex:

@Aspect
@Component
public class LoggingAspect {
    @Before("execution(* com.example.service.*.*(..))")
    public void logBefore(JoinPoint joinPoint) {
        System.out.println("Method called: " + joinPoint.getSignature());
    }
}

c. Data Access/Integration:
What it does: Simplifies database access and integration with other systems.
Submodules:
JDBC: Simplifies raw JDBC code.
ORM: Integrates with Hibernate, JPA, etc.
Transaction Management: Handles transactions declaratively.
Example: Use @Repository for DAOs, @Transactional for transaction management.

@Repository
public class UserRepository {
    // Data access code
}

@Service
public class UserService {
    @Transactional
    public void createUser(User user) {
        // Transactional code
    }
}

d. Web Module:
What it does: Supports web application development.
Submodules:
Spring MVC: For building REST APIs and web apps using the Servlet API.
Spring WebFlux: For reactive, non-blocking web applications.
Example: Use @Controller, @RestController, @RequestMapping.


@RestController
@RequestMapping("/users")
public class UserController {
    @GetMapping("/{id}")
    public User getUser(@PathVariable Long id) {
        // Return user
    }
}

e. Testing Module
What it does: Provides support for unit and integration testing.
Example: Use @SpringBootTest, @MockBean, etc.


@SpringBootTest
public class UserServiceTest {
    @Autowired
    private UserService userService;

    @Test
    public void testCreateUser() {
        // Test logic
    }
}


The Broader Spring Ecosystem:

Spring Boot: Makes it easy to create stand-alone, production-ready Spring applications with minimal configuration.
Spring Data: Simplifies data access, especially with JPA and NoSQL databases.
Spring Security: Adds authentication and authorization.
Spring Cloud: For building distributed systems and microservices.
Spring AI: Newer project for integrating AI features.


Module	                     Purpose	                          Key Annotations/Classes

Core	                     IoC, DI, bean management	          @Component, @Autowired
AOP	                         Cross-cutting concerns	              @Aspect, @Before, @After
Data Access	                 Database, ORM, transactions	      @Repository, @Transactional
Web	                         REST APIs, web apps	              @Controller, @RestController
Testing	                     Unit/integration testing	          @SpringBootTest, @MockBean